The goal of the project was to support student participation at the Computer Human-Interaction Mentoring (CHIME) Workshop, part of the Discipline-Specific Workshops sponsored in part by the CRA (http://www.cra-w.org/cdc). The workshop provided an opportunity for networking and mentoring among a diverse group of students in the area of human-computer interaction (HCI). The explicit goals were:

Help the students build relationships/networks with their peers;
Help students build relationships/networks with leaders in their field;
Provide a welcoming environment for mentoring and collaboration;
Encourage the students' participation in the leading research venue in their field.


The workshop included a series of presentations, panels, and a poster session designed to inform, inspire, and encourage future research in HCI. All 30 students participating were enrolled in Ph.D. programs at 22 institutions in the United States and Canada. The ethnic breakdown included: 10 African Americans, 8 Caucasians, 6 Hispanics, 1 Native American, and 3 Asian Americans (3 classified themselves as "other"). The gender breakdown: 8 male and 22 female participants. The speakers at the workshop also showed similar diverse composition.

The workshop evaluation showed that the sessions were well received and that participants are likely to follow up with the speakers to establish further technical collaborations after the workshop.

